This involves upgrading our linters, since flake8 has a more recent
version of both pep8 and pyflakes than we're using.  I made sure
webapp still passes lint after this change though.  Various other
repos do not, but most of them didn't pass lint at all -- e.g. they
had lines >80 columns that even our own linters were catching.  I'll
make a not-too-big effort to clean them all up before this is live.
The new code is more efficient than the old because we can take
advantage of the multiprocessing that flake8 can do!  This may end up
overloading the CPUs when we run the lints via tests, because that
also splits up linting across processors, but it should be ok on
jenkins (where tests run on 1-CPU machines), which is the only place
lint_test.py is run in practice.  Locally, via `make linc` and
similar, we should see a nice speedup.
I moved some webapp-specific lint checks out of khan-linter; they live
in webapp now (or will once D42676 is landed).  That simplifies the
flake8 linter enough that I think it's now easier to read, even though
it now encompasses everything that used to be in both pep8 and pyflakes.

Refactored object expirer to use this client.
This change replaces WebOb with a mostly compatible local library,
swift.common.swob.  Subtle changes to WebOb's API over the years have been a
huge headache.  Swift doesn't even run on the current version.
There are a few incompatibilities to simplify the implementation/interface:
* It only implements the header properties we use.  More can be easily added.
* Casts header values to str on assignment.
* Response classes (""HTTPNotFound"") are no longer subclasses, but partials
on Response, so things like isinstance no longer work on them.
* Unlike newer webob versions, will never return unicode objects.
made internal client handle unicode path parts by adding make_path method
fixed pep8 problems in internal client and its test
moved internal client unit test file to correct directory

In two places, the internal client was not doing what it should with failed requests.
